etical analyses and selected case studies, Federal Democracies at Work contributes to our understanding of the complex relations between federalism and democracy. Throughout the volume, contributing authors elaborate and apply an innovative analytical framework to provide greater clarity on the complex relations between federalism and democracy. As a whole, the volume explores how different institutional configurations of federal democracies alleviate or intensify inherent tensions; how actors grapple and cope with the challenge of these complexities; and how structures evolve as a result of rising conflicts and institutional reforms or adjustments. In doing so, Federal Democracies at Work advances research on comparative federalism and works toward a better understanding of how these compound systems work.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aComparative government. 0aDemocracy. 0aFederal government. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aaccountability.  aconstitution.  ademocracy.  adivision of power.  afederalism.  aintergovernmental relations.  aparliament.  aparties.  arepresentation.1 aAustralian, Anthony Sayers, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBanfield, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenz, Arthur, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenz, Arthur, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBroschek, Jörg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBursens, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColino, César, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConlan, Timothy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFossum, John Erik, econtributor.4ctb4h